# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: optical-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] An **optical add-drop multiplexer** (**OADM**) is a device used in wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM) systems for multiplexing and routing different channels of light into or out of a single-mode fiber (SMF).
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] This is a type of optical node, which is generally used for the formation and the construction of optical telecommunications networks.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] "Add" and "drop" here refer to the capability of the device to add one or more new wavelength channels to an existing multi-wavelength WDM signal, and/or to drop (remove) one or more channels, passing those signals to another network path.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] An OADM may be considered to be a specific type of optical cross-connect.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] A traditional OADM consists of three stages: an optical demultiplexer, an optical multiplexer, and between them a method of reconfiguring the paths between the demultiplexer, the multiplexer and a set of ports for adding and dropping signals.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] The demultiplexer separates wavelengths in an input fiber onto ports.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] The reconfiguration can be achieved by a fiber patch panel or by optical switches which direct the wavelengths to the multiplexer or to drop ports.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] The multiplexer multiplexes the wavelength channels that are to continue on from demultiplexer ports with those from the add ports, onto a single output fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] All the lightpaths that directly pass an OADM are termed *cut-through lightpaths*, while those that are added or dropped at the OADM node are termed *added/dropped lightpaths*.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] An OADM with remotely reconfigurable optical switches (for example 1×2) in the middle stage is called a reconfigurable OADM (ROADM).
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] Ones without this feature are known as *fixed* OADMs.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] While the term OADM applies to both types, it is often used interchangeably with ROADM.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] Physically, there are several ways to make an OADM.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] There are a variety of demultiplexer and multiplexer technologies including thin film filters, fiber Bragg gratings with optical circulators, free space grating devices and integrated planar arrayed waveguide gratings.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] The switching or reconfiguration functions range from the manual fiber patch panel to a variety of switching technologies including microelectromechanical systems (MEMS), liquid crystal and thermo-optic switches in planar waveguide circuits.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] Although both have add/drop functionality, OADMs are distinct from add-drop multiplexers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] The former function in the photonic domain under wavelength-division multiplexing, while the latter are implicitly considered to function in the traditional SONET/SDH networks.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] An **optical amplifier** is a device that amplifies an optical signal directly, without the need to first convert it to an electrical signal.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] An optical amplifier may be thought of as a laser without an optical cavity, or one in which feedback from the cavity is suppressed.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Optical amplifiers are important in optical communication and laser physics.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] They are used as optical repeaters in the long distance fiber-optic cables which carry much of the world's telecommunication links.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] There are several different physical mechanisms that can be used to amplify a light signal, which correspond to the major types of optical amplifiers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In doped fiber amplifiers and bulk lasers, stimulated emission in the amplifier's gain medium causes amplification of incoming light.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In semiconductor optical amplifiers (SOAs), electron–hole recombination occurs.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In Raman amplifiers, Raman scattering of incoming light with phonons in the lattice of the gain medium produces photons coherent with the incoming photons.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Parametric amplifiers use parametric amplification.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The principle of optical amplification was invented by Gordon Gould on November 13, 1957.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] He filed US Patent US80453959A on April 6, 1959, titled "Light Amplifiers Employing Collisions to Produce Population Inversions" (subsequently amended as a continuation in part and finally issued as U.S. patent 4,746,201A on May 4, 1988).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The patent covered “the amplification of light by the stimulated emission of photons from ions, atoms or molecules in gaseous, liquid or solid state.” In total, Gould obtained 48 patents related to the optical amplifier that covered 80% of the lasers on the market at the time of issuance.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Gould co-founded an optical telecommunications equipment firm, Optelecom Inc., that helped start Ciena Corp with his former head of Light Optics Research, David Huber and Kevin Kimberlin.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Huber and Steve Alexander of Ciena invented the dual-stage optical amplifier (U.S. patent 5,159,601) that was a key to the first dense wave division multiplexing (DWDM) system, that they released in June 1996.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] This marked the start of optical networking.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Optical amplification WDM systems are the common basis of all local, metro, national, intercontinental and subsea telecommunications networks and the technology of choice for the fiber optic backbones of the Internet (e.g. fiber-optic cables form a basis of modern-day computer networking).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Almost any laser active gain medium can be pumped to produce gain for light at the wavelength of a laser made with the same material as its gain medium.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Such amplifiers are commonly used to produce high power laser systems.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Special types such as regenerative amplifiers and chirped-pulse amplifiers are used to amplify ultrashort pulses.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Amplification is achieved by stimulated emission of photons from dopant ions in the doped fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The pump laser excites ions into a higher energy from where they can decay via stimulated emission of a photon at the signal wavelength back to a lower energy level.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The excited ions can also decay spontaneously (spontaneous emission) or even through nonradiative processes involving interactions with phonons of the glass matrix.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] These last two decay mechanisms compete with stimulated emission reducing the efficiency of light amplification.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The *amplification window* of an optical amplifier is the range of optical wavelengths for which the amplifier yields a usable gain.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The amplification window is determined by the spectroscopic properties of the dopant ions, the glass structure of the optical fiber, and the wavelength and power of the pump laser.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Although the electronic transitions of an isolated ion are very well defined, broadening of the energy levels occurs when the ions are incorporated into the glass of the optical fiber and thus the amplification window is also broadened.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] This broadening is both homogeneous (all ions exhibit the same broadened spectrum) and inhomogeneous (different ions in different glass locations exhibit different spectra).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Homogeneous broadening arises from the interactions with phonons of the glass, while inhomogeneous broadening is caused by differences in the glass sites where different ions are hosted.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Different sites expose ions to different local electric fields, which shifts the energy levels via the Stark effect.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In addition, the Stark effect also removes the degeneracy of energy states having the same total angular momentum (specified by the quantum number J).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Thus, for example, the trivalent erbium ion (Er3+) has a ground state with J = 15/2, and in the presence of an electric field splits into J + 1/2 = 8 sublevels with slightly different energies.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The first excited state has J = 13/2 and therefore a Stark manifold with 7 sublevels.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Transitions from the J = 13/2 excited state to the J= 15/2 ground state are responsible for the gain at 1500 nm wavelength.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The gain spectrum of the EDFA has several peaks that are smeared by the above broadening mechanisms.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The net result is a very broad spectrum (30 nm in silica, typically).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The broad gain-bandwidth of fiber amplifiers make them particularly useful in wavelength-division multiplexed communications systems as a single amplifier can be utilized to amplify all signals being carried on a fiber and whose wavelengths fall within the gain window.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] An *erbium-doped waveguide amplifier* (EDWA) is an optical amplifier that uses a waveguide to boost an optical signal.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] A relatively high-powered beam of light known as the pump light is mixed with the amplified input signal using a coupler.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The input signal and the pump light must be at significantly different wavelengths.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The mixed light is guided into a section of fiber with erbium ions included in the core.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] This high-powered light beam excites the erbium ions to their higher-energy state.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] When the photons belonging to the signal at a different wavelength from the pump light meet the excited erbium ions, the erbium ions undergo stimulated emission and return to their lower-energy state.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] A significant point is that the erbium gives up its energy in the form of additional photons which are exactly in the same phase, frequency, and direction as the signal being amplified.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] So the signal is amplified along its direction of travel only.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] This is not unusual – when an atom "lases" it always gives up its energy in the same direction and phase as the incoming light.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Thus all of the additional signal power is guided in the same fiber mode as the incoming signal.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The pump light can be sent into the fiber in the same direction (forward pumping) or opposite direction of the signal (backwards pumping).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] An optical isolator is usually placed at the output to prevent reflections returning from the attached fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Such reflections disrupt amplifier operation and in the extreme case can cause the amplifier to become a laser.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The erbium doped amplifier is a high gain amplifier.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The principal source of noise in DFAs is amplified spontaneous emission (ASE), which has a spectrum approximately the same as the gain spectrum of the amplifier.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Noise figure in an ideal DFA is 3 dB, while practical amplifiers can have noise figure as large as 6–8 dB.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] As well as decaying via stimulated emission, electrons in the upper energy level can also decay by spontaneous emission, which occurs at random, depending upon the glass structure and inversion level.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Photons are emitted spontaneously in all directions, but a proportion of those will be emitted in a direction that falls within the numerical aperture of the fiber and are thus captured and guided by the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Those photons captured may then interact with other dopant ions, and are thus amplified by stimulated emission.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The initial spontaneous emission is therefore amplified in the same manner as the signals, hence the term a*mplified spontaneous emission*.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] ASE is emitted by the amplifier in both the forward and reverse directions, but only the forward ASE is a direct concern to system performance since that noise will co-propagate with the signal to the receiver where it degrades system performance.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Counter-propagating ASE can, however, lead to degradation of the amplifier's performance since the ASE can deplete the inversion level and thereby reduce the gain of the amplifier and increase the noise produced relative to the desired signal gain.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Noise figure can be analyzed in both the optical domain and in the electrical domain.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In the optical domain, measurement of the ASE, the optical signal gain, and signal wavelength using an optical spectrum analyzer permits calculation of the noise figure.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] For the electrical measurement method, the detected photocurrent noise is evaluated with a low-noise electrical spectrum analyzer, which along with measurement of the amplifier gain permits a noise figure measurement.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Generally, the optical technique provides a more simple method, though it is not inclusive of excess noise effects captured by the electrical method such multi-path interference (MPI) noise generation.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In both methods, attention to effects such as the spontaneous emission accompanying the input signal are critical to accurate measurement of noise figure.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Gain is achieved in a DFA due to population inversion of the dopant ions.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The inversion level of a DFA is set, primarily, by the power of the pump wavelength and the power at the amplified wavelengths.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] As the signal power increases, or the pump power decreases, the inversion level will reduce and thereby the gain of the amplifier will be reduced.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] This effect is known as gain saturation – as the signal level increases, the amplifier saturates and cannot produce any more output power, and therefore the gain reduces.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Saturation is also commonly known as gain compression.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] To achieve optimum noise performance DFAs are operated under a significant amount of gain compression (10 dB typically), since that reduces the rate of spontaneous emission, thereby reducing ASE.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Another advantage of operating the DFA in the gain saturation region is that small fluctuations in the input signal power are reduced in the output amplified signal: smaller input signal powers experience larger (less saturated) gain, while larger input powers see less gain.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The leading edge of the pulse is amplified, until the saturation energy of the gain medium is reached.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In some condition, the width (FWHM) of the pulse is reduced.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Due to the inhomogeneous portion of the linewidth broadening of the dopant ions, the gain spectrum has an inhomogeneous component and gain saturation occurs, to a small extent, in an inhomogeneous manner.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] This effect is known as *spectral hole burning* because a high power signal at one wavelength can 'burn' a hole in the gain for wavelengths close to that signal by saturation of the inhomogeneously broadened ions.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Spectral holes vary in width depending on the characteristics of the optical fiber in question and the power of the burning signal, but are typically less than 1 nm at the short wavelength end of the C-band, and a few nm at the long wavelength end of the C-band.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The depth of the holes are very small, though, making it difficult to observe in practice.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Although the DFA is essentially a polarization independent amplifier, a small proportion of the dopant ions interact preferentially with certain polarizations and a small dependence on the polarization of the input signal may occur (typically < 0.5 dB).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] This is called polarization dependent gain (PDG).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The absorption and emission cross sections of the ions can be modeled as ellipsoids with the major axes aligned at random in all directions in different glass sites.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The random distribution of the orientation of the ellipsoids in a glass produces a macroscopically isotropic medium, but a strong pump laser induces an anisotropic distribution by selectively exciting those ions that are more aligned with the optical field vector of the pump.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Also, those excited ions aligned with the signal field produce more stimulated emission.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The change in gain is thus dependent on the alignment of the polarizations of the pump and signal lasers – i.e. whether the two lasers are interacting with the same sub-set of dopant ions or not.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In an ideal doped fiber without birefringence, the PDG would be inconveniently large.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Fortunately, in optical fibers small amounts of birefringence are always present and, furthermore, the fast and slow axes vary randomly along the fiber length.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] A typical DFA has several tens of meters, long enough to already show this randomness of the birefringence axes.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] These two combined effects (which in transmission fibers give rise to polarization mode dispersion) produce a misalignment of the relative polarizations of the signal and pump lasers along the fiber, thus tending to average out the PDG.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The result is that PDG is very difficult to observe in a single amplifier (but is noticeable in links with several cascaded amplifiers).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The erbium-doped fiber amplifier (EDFA) is the most deployed fiber amplifier as its amplification window coincides with the third transmission window of silica-based optical fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The core of a silica fiber is doped with trivalent erbium ions (Er3+) and can be efficiently pumped with a laser at or near wavelengths of 980 nm and 1480 nm, and gain is exhibited in the 1550 nm region.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The EDFA amplification region varies from application to application and can be anywhere from a few nm up to ~80 nm.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Typical use of EDFA in telecommunications calls for *Conventional*, or C-band amplifiers (from ~1525 nm to ~1565 nm) or *Long*, or L-band amplifiers (from ~1565 nm to ~1610 nm).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Both of these bands can be amplified by EDFAs, but it is normal to use two different amplifiers, each optimized for one of the bands.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The principal difference between C- and L-band amplifiers is that a longer length of doped fiber is used in L-band amplifiers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The longer length of fiber allows a lower inversion level to be used, thereby giving emission at longer wavelengths (due to the band-structure of Erbium in silica) while still providing a useful amount of gain.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] EDFAs have two commonly used pumping bands – 980 nm and 1480 nm.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The 980 nm band has a higher absorption cross-section and is generally used where low-noise performance is required.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The absorption band is relatively narrow and so wavelength stabilised laser sources are typically needed.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The 1480 nm band has a lower, but broader, absorption cross-section and is generally used for higher power amplifiers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] A combination of 980 nm and 1480 nm pumping is generally utilised in amplifiers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Gain and lasing in erbium-doped fibers were first demonstrated in 1986–87 by two groups; one including David N.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Reekie, from the University of Southampton and one from AT&T Bell Laboratories, consisting of E.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The dual-stage optical amplifier which enabled dense wave division multiplexing (DWDM) was invented by Stephen B.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Thulium doped fiber amplifiers have been used in the S-band (1450–1490 nm) and Praseodymium doped amplifiers in the 1300 nm region.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] However, those regions have not seen any significant commercial use so far and so those amplifiers have not been the subject of as much development as the EDFA.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] However, Ytterbium doped fiber lasers and amplifiers, operating near 1 micrometre wavelength, have many applications in industrial processing of materials, as these devices can be made with extremely high output power (tens of kilowatts).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Semiconductor optical amplifiers (SOAs) are amplifiers which use a semiconductor to provide the gain medium.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] These amplifiers have a similar structure to Fabry–Pérot laser diodes but with anti-reflection design elements at the end faces.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Recent designs include anti-reflective coatings and tilted wave guide and window regions which can reduce end face reflection to less than 0.001%.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Since this creates a loss of power from the cavity which is greater than the gain, it prevents the amplifier from acting as a laser.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Another type of SOA consists of two regions.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] One part has a structure of a Fabry-Pérot laser diode and the other has a tapered geometry in order to reduce the power density on the output facet.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Semiconductor optical amplifiers are typically made from group III-V compound semiconductors such as GaAs/AlGaAs, InP/InGaAs, InP/InGaAsP and InP/InAlGaAs, though any direct band gap semiconductors such as II-VI could conceivably be used.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Such amplifiers are often used in telecommunication systems in the form of fiber-pigtailed components, operating at signal wavelengths between 850 nm and 1600 nm and generating gains of up to 30 dB.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The semiconductor optical amplifier is of small size and electrically pumped.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] It can be potentially less expensive than the EDFA and can be integrated with semiconductor lasers, modulators, etc.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] However, the performance is still not comparable with the EDFA.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The SOA has higher noise, lower gain, moderate polarization dependence and high nonlinearity with fast transient time.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The main advantage of SOA is that all four types of nonlinear operations (cross gain modulation, cross phase modulation, wavelength conversion and four wave mixing) can be conducted.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Furthermore, SOA can be run with a low power laser.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] This originates from the short nanosecond or less upper state lifetime, so that the gain reacts rapidly to changes of pump or signal power and the changes of gain also cause phase changes which can distort the signals.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] This nonlinearity presents the most severe problem for optical communication applications.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] However it provides the possibility for gain in different wavelength regions from the EDFA.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] "Linear optical amplifiers" using gain-clamping techniques have been developed.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] High optical nonlinearity makes semiconductor amplifiers attractive for all optical signal processing like all-optical switching and wavelength conversion.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] There has been much research on semiconductor optical amplifiers as elements for optical signal processing, wavelength conversion, clock recovery, signal demultiplexing, and pattern recognition.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] A recent addition to the SOA family is the vertical-cavity SOA (VCSOA).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] These devices are similar in structure to, and share many features with, vertical-cavity surface-emitting lasers (VCSELs).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The major difference when comparing VCSOAs and VCSELs is the reduced mirror reflectivity used in the amplifier cavity.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] With VCSOAs, reduced feedback is necessary to prevent the device from reaching lasing threshold.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Due to the extremely short cavity length, and correspondingly thin gain medium, these devices exhibit very low single-pass gain (typically on the order of a few percent) and also a very large free spectral range (FSR).
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The small single-pass gain requires relatively high mirror reflectivity to boost the total signal gain.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In addition to boosting the total signal gain, the use of the resonant cavity structure results in a very narrow gain bandwidth; coupled with the large FSR of the optical cavity, this effectively limits operation of the VCSOA to single-channel amplification.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Thus, VCSOAs can be seen as amplifying filters.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Given their vertical-cavity geometry, VCSOAs are resonant cavity optical amplifiers that operate with the input/output signal entering/exiting normal to the wafer surface.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In addition to their small size, the surface normal operation of VCSOAs leads to a number of advantages, including low power consumption, low noise figure, polarization insensitive gain, and the ability to fabricate high fill factor two-dimensional arrays on a single semiconductor chip.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] These devices are still in the early stages of research, though promising preamplifier results have been demonstrated.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Further extensions to VCSOA technology are the demonstration of wavelength tunable devices.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] These MEMS-tunable vertical-cavity SOAs utilize a microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) based tuning mechanism for wide and continuous tuning of the peak gain wavelength of the amplifier.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] SOAs have a more rapid gain response, which is in the order of 1 to 100 ps.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] For high output power and broader wavelength range, tapered amplifiers are used.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] These amplifiers consist of a lateral single-mode section and a section with a tapered structure, where the laser light is amplified.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The tapered structure leads to a reduction of the power density at the output facet.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In a Raman amplifier, the signal is intensified by Raman amplification.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Unlike the EDFA and SOA the amplification effect is achieved by a nonlinear interaction between the signal and a pump laser within an optical fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] There are two types of Raman amplifier: distributed and lumped.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] A distributed Raman amplifier is one in which the transmission fiber is utilised as the gain medium by multiplexing a pump wavelength with signal wavelength, while a lumped Raman amplifier utilises a dedicated, shorter length of fiber to provide amplification.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In the case of a lumped Raman amplifier, a highly nonlinear fiber with a small core is utilised to increase the interaction between signal and pump wavelengths, and thereby reduce the length of fiber required.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The pump light may be coupled into the transmission fiber in the same direction as the signal (co-directional pumping), in the opposite direction (contra-directional pumping) or both.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Contra-directional pumping is more common as the transfer of noise from the pump to the signal is reduced.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The pump power required for Raman amplification is higher than that required by the EDFA, with in excess of 500 mW being required to achieve useful levels of gain in a distributed amplifier.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Lumped amplifiers, where the pump light can be safely contained to avoid safety implications of high optical powers, may use over 1 W of optical power.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The principal advantage of Raman amplification is its ability to provide distributed amplification within the transmission fiber, thereby increasing the length of spans between amplifier and regeneration sites.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] The amplification bandwidth of Raman amplifiers is defined by the pump wavelengths utilised and so amplification can be provided over wider, and different, regions than may be possible with other amplifier types which rely on dopants and device design to define the amplification 'window'.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Raman amplifiers have some fundamental advantages.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] First, Raman gain exists in every fiber, which provides a cost-effective means of upgrading from the terminal ends.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Second, the gain is nonresonant, which means that gain is available over the entire transparency region of the fiber ranging from approximately 0.3 to 2 μm.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] A third advantage of Raman amplifiers is that the gain spectrum can be tailored by adjusting the pump wavelengths.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] For instance, multiple pump lines can be used to increase the optical bandwidth, and the pump distribution determines the gain flatness.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Another advantage of Raman amplification is that it is a relatively broad-band amplifier with a bandwidth > 5 THz, and the gain is reasonably flat over a wide wavelength range.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] However, a number of challenges for Raman amplifiers prevented their earlier adoption.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] First, compared to the EDFAs, Raman amplifiers have relatively poor pumping efficiency at lower signal powers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Although a disadvantage, this lack of pump efficiency also makes gain clamping easier in Raman amplifiers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Second, Raman amplifiers require a longer gain fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] However, this disadvantage can be mitigated by combining gain and the dispersion compensation in a single fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] A third disadvantage of Raman amplifiers is a fast response time, which gives rise to new sources of noise, as further discussed below.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Finally, there are concerns of nonlinear penalty in the amplifier for the WDM signal channels.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] An optical parametric amplifier allows the amplification of a weak signal-impulse in a nonlinear medium such as a noncentrosymmetric nonlinear medium (e.g.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Beta barium borate (BBO)) or even a standard fused silica optical fiber via the Kerr effect.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In contrast to the previously mentioned amplifiers, which are mostly used in telecommunication environments, this type finds its main application in expanding the frequency tunability of ultrafast solid-state lasers (e.g.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] By using a noncollinear interaction geometry optical parametric amplifiers are capable of extremely broad amplification bandwidths.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] In the 21st century high power fiber lasers were adopted as an industrial material processing tool, and were expanding into other markets including the medical and scientific markets.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] One key enhancement enabling penetration into the scientific market was improvement in high finesse fiber amplifiers, which became able to deliver single frequency linewidths (<5 kHz) together with excellent beam quality and stable linearly polarized output.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Systems meeting these specifications steadily progressed from a few watts of output power initially, to tens of watts and later hundreds of watts.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] As of 2015 high finesse, high power and pulsed fiber amplifiers delivered power levels exceeding those available from commercial solid-state single-frequency sources, and stable optimized performance, opening up new scientific applications.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] There are several simulation tools that can be used to design optical amplifiers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-amplifier] Popular commercial tools have been developed by Optiwave Systems and VPI Systems.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] An optical communication system uses a transmitter, which encodes a message into an optical signal, a channel, which carries the signal to its destination, and a receiver, which reproduces the message from the received optical signal.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] When electronic equipment is not employed the 'receiver' is a person visually observing and interpreting a signal, which may be either simple (such as the presence of a beacon fire) or complex (such as lights using color codes or flashed in a Morse code sequence).
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Modern communication relies on optical networking systems using optical fiber, optical amplifiers, lasers, switches, routers, and other related technologies.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Free-space optical communication use lasers to transmit signals in space, while terrestrial forms are naturally limited by geography and weather.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] This article provides a basic introduction to different forms of optical communication.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Visual techniques such as smoke signals, beacon fires, hydraulic telegraphs, ship flags and semaphore lines were the earliest forms of optical communication.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Hydraulic telegraph semaphores date back to the 4th century BCE Greece.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Distress flares are still used by mariners in emergencies, while lighthouses and navigation lights are used to communicate navigation hazards.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The heliograph uses a mirror to reflect sunlight to a distant observer.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] When a signaler tilts the mirror to reflect sunlight, the distant observer sees flashes of light that can be used to transmit a prearranged signaling code.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Naval ships often use signal lamps and Morse code in a similar way.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Aircraft pilots often use visual approach slope indicator (VASI) projected light systems to land safely, especially at night.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Military aircraft landing on an aircraft carrier use a similar system to land correctly on a carrier deck.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The coloured light system communicates the aircraft's height relative to a standard landing glideslope.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] As well, airport control towers still use Aldis lamps to transmit instructions to aircraft whose radios have failed.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] A 'semaphore telegraph', also called a 'semaphore line', 'optical telegraph', 'shutter telegraph chain', 'Chappe telegraph', or 'Napoleonic semaphore', is a system used for conveying information by means of visual signals, using towers with pivoting arms or shutters, also known as blades or paddles.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Information is encoded by the position of the mechanical elements; it is read when the shutter is in a fixed position.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Semaphore lines were a precursor of the electrical telegraph.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] They were far faster than post riders for conveying a message over long distances, but far more expensive and less private than the electrical telegraph lines which would later replace them.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The maximum distance that a pair of semaphore telegraph stations can bridge is limited by geography, weather and the availability of light; thus, in practical use, most optical telegraphs used lines of relay stations to bridge longer distances.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Each relay station would also require its complement of skilled operator-observers to convey messages back and forth across the line.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The modern design of semaphores was first foreseen by the British polymath Robert Hooke, who first gave a vivid and comprehensive outline of visual telegraphy in a 1684 submission to the Royal Society.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] His proposal (which was motivated by military concerns following the Battle of Vienna the preceding year) was not put into practice during his lifetime.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The first operational optical semaphore line arrived in 1792, created by the French engineer Claude Chappe and his brothers, who succeeded in covering France with a network of 556 stations stretching a total distance of 4,800 kilometres (3,000 mi).
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] It was used for military and national communications until the 1850s.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Many national services adopted signaling systems different from the Chappe system.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] For example, Britain and Sweden adopted systems of shuttered panels (in contradiction to the Chappe brothers' contention that angled rods are more visible).
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] In Spain, the engineer Agustín de Betancourt developed his own system which was adopted by that state.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] This system was considered by many experts in Europe better than Chappe's, even in France.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] These systems were popular in the late 18th to early 19th century but could not compete with the electrical telegraph, and went completely out of service by 1880.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Semaphore flags are the system for conveying information at a distance by means of visual signals with hand-held flags, rods, disks, paddles, or occasionally bare or gloved hands.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Information is encoded by the position of the flags, objects or arms; it is read when they are in a fixed position.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Semaphores were adopted and widely used (with hand-held flags replacing the mechanical arms of shutter semaphores) in the maritime world in the 19th century.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] They are still used during underway replenishment at sea and are acceptable for emergency communication in daylight or, using lighted wands instead of flags, at night.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The newer flag semaphore system uses two short poles with square flags, which a signaler holds in different positions to convey letters of the alphabet and numbers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The transmitter holds one pole in each hand, and extends each arm in one of eight possible directions.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Except for in the rest position, the flags cannot overlap.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The flags are colored differently based on whether the signals are sent by sea or by land.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] At sea, the flags are colored red and yellow (the Oscar flags), while on land, they are white and blue (the Papa flags).
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Flags are not required, they just make the characters more obvious.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Signal lamps (such as Aldis lamps), are visual signaling devices for optical communication (typically using Morse code).
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Modern signal lamps are a focused lamp which can produce a pulse of light.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] In large versions this pulse is achieved by opening and closing shutters mounted in front of the lamp, either via a manually operated pressure switch or, in later versions, automatically.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] With hand held lamps, a concave mirror is tilted by a trigger to focus the light into pulses.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The lamps are usually equipped with some form of optical sight, and are most commonly deployed on naval vessels and also used in airport control towers with coded aviation light signals.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Aviation light signals are used in the case of a radio failure, an aircraft not equipped with a radio, or in the case of a hearing-impaired pilot.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Air traffic controllers have long used signal light guns to direct such aircraft.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The light gun's lamp has a focused bright beam capable of emitting three different colors: red, white and green.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] These colors may be flashing or steady, and provide different instructions to aircraft in flight or on the ground (for example, "cleared to land" or "cleared for takeoff").
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Pilots can acknowledge the instructions by wiggling their plane's wings, moving their ailerons if they are on the ground, or by flashing their landing or navigation lights during night time.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Only 12 simple standardized instructions are directed at aircraft using signal light guns as the system is not utilized with Morse code.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] A heliograph (Greek: Ἥλιος *helios*, meaning "sun", and γραφειν *graphein*, meaning "write") is a wireless solar telegraph that signals by flashes of sunlight (generally using Morse code) reflected by a mirror.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The flashes are produced by momentarily pivoting the mirror, or by interrupting the beam with a shutter.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The heliograph was a simple but effective instrument for instantaneous optical communication over long distances during the late 19th and early 20th century.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Its main uses were in military, surveys and forest protection work.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] They were standard issue in the British and Australian armies until the 1960s, and were used by the Pakistani army as late as 1975.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] In the present day a variety of electronic systems optically transmit and receive information carried by pulses of light.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Fiber-optic communication cables are employed to carry electronic data and telephone traffic.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Free-space optical communications are also used every day in various applications.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Optical fiber is the most common type of channel for optical communications.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The transmitters in optical fiber links are generally light-emitting diodes (LEDs) or laser diodes.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Infrared light is used more commonly than visible light, because optical fibers transmit infrared wavelengths with less attenuation and dispersion.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The signal encoding is typically simple intensity modulation, although historically optical phase and frequency modulation have been demonstrated in the lab.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The need for periodic signal regeneration was largely superseded by the introduction of the erbium-doped fiber amplifier, which extended link distances at significantly lower cost.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The commercial introduction of dense wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM) in 1996 by Ciena Corp was the real start of optical networking.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] WDM is now the common basis of nearly every high-capacity optical system in the world.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The first optical communication systems were designed and delivered to the U.S.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Army and Chevron by Optelecom, Inc., the venture co-founded by Gordon Gould, the inventor of the optical amplifier and the laser.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The photophone (originally given an alternate name, radiophone) is a communication device which allowed for the transmission of speech on a beam of light.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] It was invented jointly by Alexander Graham Bell and his assistant Charles Sumner Tainter on February 19, 1880, at Bell's 1325 'L' Street laboratory in Washington, D.C.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Both were later to become full associates in the Volta Laboratory Association, created and financed by Bell.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] On June 21, 1880, Bell's assistant transmitted a wireless voice telephone message of considerable distance, from the roof of the Franklin School to the window of Bell's laboratory, some 213 meters (about 700 ft) away.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Bell believed the photophone was his most important invention.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The photophone was a precursor to the fiber-optic communication systems which achieved popular worldwide usage starting in the 1980s.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] The master patent for the photophone (U.S. patent 235,199 *Apparatus for Signalling and Communicating, called Photophone*), was issued in December 1880, many decades before its principles came to have practical applications.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Free-space optics (FSO) systems are employed for 'last mile' telecommunications and can function over distances of several kilometers as long as there is a clear line of sight between the source and the destination, and the optical receiver can reliably decode the transmitted information.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Other free-space systems can provide high-data-rate, long-range links using small, low-mass, low-power-consumption subsystems which make them suitable for communications in space.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Various planned satellite constellations intended to provide global broadband coverage take advantage of these benefits and employ laser communication for inter-satellite links between the several hundred to thousand satellites effectively creating a space-based optical mesh network.
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] More generally, transmission of unguided optical signals is known as optical wireless communications (OWC).
[src:optical-networking/optical-communication] Examples include medium-range visible light communication and short-distance IrDA, using infrared LEDs.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] An **optical fiber**, or **optical fibre**, is a flexible glass or plastic fiber that can transmit light from one end to the other.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Such fibers are widely used in fiber-optic communication, where they permit transmission over longer distances and at higher bandwidths (data transfer rates) than electrical cables.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers are used instead of cables because signals travel along them with less loss and are immune to electromagnetic interference.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers are also used for illumination and imaging, and are often wrapped in bundles so they may be used to carry light into, or images out of confined spaces, as in the case of a fiberscope.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Specially designed fibers are also used for a variety of other applications, such as fiber optic sensors and fiber lasers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Glass optical fibers are typically made by drawing, while plastic fibers can be made either by drawing or by extrusion.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers typically include a core surrounded by a transparent cladding material with a lower index of refraction.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Light is kept in the core by the phenomenon of total internal reflection which causes the fiber to act as a waveguide.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers that support many propagation paths or transverse modes are called multi-mode fibers, while those that support a single mode are called single-mode fibers (SMF).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Multi-mode fibers generally have a wider core diameter and are used for short-distance communication links and for applications where high power must be transmitted.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Single-mode fibers are used for most communication links longer than 1,050 meters (3,440 ft).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Being able to join optical fibers with low loss is important in fiber optic communication.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This is more complex than joining electrical wire or cable and involves careful cleaving of the fibers, precise alignment of the fiber cores, and the coupling of these aligned cores.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] For applications that demand a permanent connection a fusion splice is common.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In this technique, an electric arc is used to melt the ends of the fibers together.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Another common technique is a mechanical splice, where the ends of the fibers are held in contact by mechanical force.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Temporary or semi-permanent connections are made by means of specialized optical fiber connectors.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The field of applied science and engineering concerned with the design and application of optical fibers is known as *fiber optics*.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The term was coined by Indian-American physicist Narinder Singh Kapany.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Daniel Colladon and Jacques Babinet first demonstrated the guiding of light by refraction, the principle that makes fiber optics possible, in Paris in the early 1840s.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] John Tyndall included a demonstration of it in his public lectures in London, 12 years later.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In the late 19th century, a team of Viennese doctors guided light through bent glass rods to illuminate body cavities.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Practical applications such as close internal illumination during dentistry followed, early in the twentieth century.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Image transmission through tubes was demonstrated independently by the radio experimenter Clarence Hansell and the television pioneer John Logie Baird in the 1920s.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In the 1930s, Heinrich Lamm showed that one could transmit images through a bundle of unclad optical fibers and used it for internal medical examinations, but his work was largely forgotten.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In 1953, Dutch scientist Bram van Heel first demonstrated image transmission through bundles of optical fibers with a transparent cladding.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Later that same year, Harold Hopkins and Narinder Singh Kapany at Imperial College in London succeeded in making image-transmitting bundles with over 10,000 fibers, and subsequently achieved image transmission through a 75 cm long bundle which combined several thousand fibers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The first practical fiber optic semi-flexible gastroscope was patented by Basil Hirschowitz, C.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Curtiss, researchers at the University of Michigan, in 1956.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In the process of developing the gastroscope, Curtiss produced the first glass-clad fibers; previous optical fibers had relied on air or impractical oils and waxes as the low-index cladding material.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Kapany coined the term *fiber optics* after writing a 1960 article in *Scientific American* that introduced the topic to a wide audience.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] He subsequently wrote the first book about the new field.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The first working fiber-optic data transmission system was demonstrated by German physicist Manfred Börner at Telefunken Research Labs in Ulm in 1965, followed by the first patent application for this technology in 1966.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In 1968, NASA used fiber optics in the television cameras that were sent to the moon.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] At the time, the use in the cameras was classified *confidential*, and employees handling the cameras had to be supervised by someone with an appropriate security clearance.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Hockham of the British company Standard Telephones and Cables (STC) were the first to promote the idea that the attenuation in optical fibers could be reduced below 20 decibels per kilometer (dB/km), making fibers a practical communication medium, in 1965.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] They proposed that the attenuation in fibers available at the time was caused by impurities that could be removed, rather than by fundamental physical effects such as scattering.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] They correctly and systematically theorized the light-loss properties for optical fiber and pointed out the right material to use for such fibers—silica glass with high purity.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This discovery earned Kao the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The crucial attenuation limit of 20 dB/km was first achieved in 1970 by researchers Robert D.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Schultz, and Frank Zimar working for American glass maker Corning Glass Works.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] They demonstrated a fiber with 17 dB/km attenuation by doping silica glass with titanium.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] A few years later, they produced a fiber with only 4 dB/km attenuation using germanium dioxide as the core dopant.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In 1981, General Electric produced fused quartz ingots that could be drawn into strands 25 miles (40 km) long.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Initially, high-quality optical fibers could only be manufactured at two meters per second.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Chemical engineer Thomas Mensah joined Corning in 1983 and increased the speed of manufacture to over 50 meters per second, making optical fiber cables cheaper than traditional copper ones.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] These innovations ushered in the era of optical fiber telecommunication.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The Italian research center CSELT worked with Corning to develop practical optical fiber cables, resulting in the first metropolitan fiber optic cable being deployed in Turin in 1977.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] CSELT also developed an early technique for splicing optical fibers, called Springroove.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation in modern optical cables is far less than in electrical copper cables, leading to long-haul fiber connections with repeater distances of 70–150 kilometers (43–93 mi).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Payne of the University of Southampton and Emmanuel Desurvire at Bell Labs, developed the erbium-doped fiber amplifier, which reduced the cost of long-distance fiber systems by reducing or eliminating optical-electrical-optical repeaters, in 1986 and 1987 respectively.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The emerging field of photonic crystals led to the development in 1991 of photonic-crystal fiber, which guides light by diffraction from a periodic structure, rather than by total internal reflection.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The first photonic crystal fibers became commercially available in 2000.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Photonic crystal fibers can carry higher power than conventional fibers and their wavelength-dependent properties can be manipulated to improve performance.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is used as a medium for telecommunication and computer networking because it is flexible and can be bundled as cables.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] It is especially advantageous for long-distance communications, because infrared light propagates through the fiber with much lower attenuation compared to electricity in electrical cables.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This allows long distances to be spanned with few repeaters.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] A data transfer rate of 10 or 40 Gbit/s is typical in deployed systems.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Using wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM) enables each fiber to carry many independent channels, each using a different wavelength of light.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The net data rate (data rate without overhead bytes) per fiber is the per-channel data rate reduced by the forward error correction (FEC) overhead, multiplied by the number of channels (usually up to 80 in commercial dense WDM systems as of 2008).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] For short-distance applications, such as a network in an office building (see fiber to the office), fiber-optic cabling can save space in cable ducts.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This is because a single fiber can carry much more data than electrical cables such as standard category 5 cable, which typically runs at 100 Mbit/s or 1 Gbit/s speeds.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers are often also used for short-distance connections between devices.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] For example, most high-definition televisions offer a digital audio optical connection.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This allows the streaming of audio over light, using the S/PDIF protocol over an optical TOSLINK connection.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber optic drones have been used in the Russo-Ukrainian War since March 2024.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] These types of drones are immune to electromagnetic interference and are not affected by electronic warfare systems.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The drones typically carry spools of glass fiber-optic cable ranging from 5 to 30 kilometres (3.1 to 18.6 mi) in length, with experimental configurations reported at up to 65 kilometres (40 mi).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Because the control signals and video feed travel through the glass core at the speed of light without generating radio emissions, the drones cannot be located or disabled by conventional radio-frequency jamming or direction-finding equipment.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Russia's Ushkuynik KVN was among the first mass-produced fiber-optic FPV loitering munitions, deployed from 2024 onward during the Russo-Ukrainian conflict.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] A physical limitation of the technology is cable snagging: if the drone maneuvers sharply through dense terrain, the trailing glass cable can catch on vegetation or structures and snap, immediately ending the mission.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are used as light guides in medical and other applications where bright light needs to be shone on a target without a clear line-of-sight path.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Many microscopes use fiber-optic light sources to provide intense illumination of samples being studied.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In some buildings, optical fibers route sunlight from the roof to other parts of the building (see nonimaging optics).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical-fiber lamps are used for illumination in decorative applications, including signs, art, toys and artificial Christmas trees.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is an intrinsic part of the light-transmitting concrete building product LiTraCon.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The bundles are led from exterior/rooftop optical light collectors through small openings or cable ducts and carry the light to where it is needed.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The optical fibers end in hybrid luminaires where the sunlight is joined with electric light, either on demand or to automatically maintain a constant light level even as the available sunlight decreases.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers have many uses in remote sensing.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In some applications, the fiber itself is the sensor (the fibers channel optical light to a processing device that analyzes changes in the light's characteristics).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In other cases, fiber is used to connect a sensor to a measurement system.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers can be used as sensors to measure strain, temperature, pressure, and other quantities by modifying a fiber so that the property being measured modulates the intensity, phase, polarization, wavelength, or transit time of light in the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Sensors that vary the intensity of light are the simplest since only a simple source and detector are required.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] A particularly useful feature of such fiber optic sensors is that they can, if required, provide distributed sensing over distances of up to one meter.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Distributed acoustic sensing is one example of this.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber can also be used in structural health monitoring.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This type of sensor can detect stresses that may have a lasting impact on structures.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] It is based on the principle of measuring analog attenuation.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In contrast, highly localized measurements can be provided by integrating miniaturized sensing elements with the tip of the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] These can be implemented by various micro- and nanofabrication technologies, such that they do not exceed the microscopic boundary of the fiber tip, allowing for such applications as insertion into blood vessels via hypodermic needle.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Extrinsic fiber optic sensors use an optical fiber cable, normally a multi-mode one, to transmit modulated light from either a non-fiber optical sensor—or an electronic sensor connected to an optical transmitter.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] A major benefit of extrinsic sensors is their ability to reach otherwise inaccessible places.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] An example is the measurement of temperature inside jet engines by using a fiber to transmit radiation into a pyrometer outside the engine.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Extrinsic sensors can be used in the same way to measure the internal temperature of electrical transformers, where the extreme electromagnetic fields present make other measurement techniques impossible.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Extrinsic sensors measure vibration, rotation, displacement, velocity, acceleration, torque, and torsion.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] A solid-state version of the gyroscope, using the interference of light, has been developed.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The fiber optic gyroscope (FOG) has no moving parts and exploits the Sagnac effect to detect mechanical rotation.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Common uses for fiber optic sensors include advanced intrusion detection security systems.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The light is transmitted along a fiber optic sensor cable placed on a fence, pipeline, or communication cabling, and the returned signal is monitored and analyzed for disturbances.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This return signal is digitally processed to detect disturbances and trip an alarm if an intrusion has occurred.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are widely used as components of optical chemical sensors and optical biosensors.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is also used in imaging optics.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] A coherent bundle of fibers is used, sometimes along with lenses, for a long, thin imaging device called an endoscope, which is used to view objects through a small hole.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Medical endoscopes are used for minimally invasive exploratory or surgical procedures.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Industrial endoscopes (see fiberscope or borescope) are used for inspecting anything hard to reach, such as jet engine interiors.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber can be used to transmit power using a photovoltaic cell to convert the light into electricity.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] While this method of power transmission is not as efficient as conventional ones, it is especially useful in situations where it is desirable not to have a metallic conductor as in the case of use near MRI machines, which produce strong magnetic fields.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Other examples are for powering electronics in high-powered antenna elements and measurement devices used in high-voltage transmission equipment.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In spectroscopy, optical fiber bundles transmit light from a spectrometer to a substance that cannot be placed inside the spectrometer itself, in order to analyze its composition.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] A spectrometer analyzes substances by bouncing light off and through them.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] By using fibers, a spectrometer can be used to study objects remotely.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] An optical fiber doped with certain rare-earth elements such as erbium can be used as the gain medium of a fiber laser or optical amplifier.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Rare-earth-doped optical fibers can be used to provide signal amplification by splicing a short section of doped fiber into a regular (undoped) optical fiber line.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The doped fiber is optically pumped with a second laser wavelength that is coupled into the line in addition to the signal wave.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Both wavelengths of light are transmitted through the doped fiber, which transfers energy from the second pump wavelength to the signal wave.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The process that causes the amplification is stimulated emission.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is also widely exploited as a nonlinear medium.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The glass medium supports a host of nonlinear optical interactions, and the long interaction lengths possible in fiber facilitate a variety of phenomena, which are harnessed for applications and fundamental investigation.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Conversely, fiber nonlinearity can have deleterious effects on optical signals, and measures are often required to minimize such unwanted effects.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers doped with a wavelength shifter collect scintillation light in physics experiments.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber-optic sights for handguns, rifles, and shotguns use pieces of optical fiber to improve the visibility of markings on the sight.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are used as components in e-textiles.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This was first done by Harry Wainwright in the 1980s.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] An optical fiber is a cylindrical dielectric waveguide (nonconducting waveguide) that transmits light along its axis through the process of total internal reflection.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The fiber consists of a *core* surrounded by a cladding layer, both of which are made of dielectric materials.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] To confine the optical signal in the core, the refractive index of the core must be greater than that of the cladding.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The boundary between the core and cladding may either be abrupt, in *step-index fiber*, or gradual, in *graded-index fiber*.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Light can be fed into optical fibers using lasers or LEDs.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are immune to electrical interference as there is no cross-talk between signals in different cables and no pickup of environmental noise.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Information traveling inside the optical fiber is even immune to electromagnetic pulses generated by nuclear devices.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber cables do not conduct electricity, which makes them useful for protecting communications equipment in high voltage environments such as power generation facilities or applications prone to lightning strikes.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The electrical isolation also prevents problems with ground loops.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Because there is no electricity in optical cables that could potentially generate sparks, they can be used in environments where explosive fumes are present.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Wiretapping (in this case, fiber tapping) is more difficult compared to electrical connections.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber cables are not targeted for metal theft.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In contrast, copper cable systems use large amounts of copper and have been targeted since the 2000s commodities boom.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The refractive index is a way of measuring the speed of light in a material.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Light travels fastest in a vacuum, such as in outer space.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The speed of light in vacuum is about 300,000 kilometers (186,000 miles) per second.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The refractive index of a medium is calculated by dividing the speed of light in vacuum by the speed of light in that medium.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The refractive index of vacuum is therefore 1, by definition.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] A typical single-mode fiber used for telecommunications has a cladding made of pure silica, with an index of 1.444 at 1500 nm, and a core of doped silica with an index around 1.4475.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The larger the index of refraction, the slower light travels in that medium.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] From this information, a simple rule of thumb is that a signal using optical fiber for communication will travel at around 200,000 kilometers per second.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Thus a phone call carried by fiber between Sydney and New York, a 16,000-kilometer distance, means that there is a minimum delay of 80 milliseconds (about ${\tfrac {1}{12}}$ of a second) between when one caller speaks and the other hears.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] When light traveling in an optically dense medium hits a boundary at a steep angle of incidence (larger than the critical angle for the boundary), the light is completely reflected.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This is called total internal reflection.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This effect is used in optical fibers to confine light in the core.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Most modern optical fiber is *weakly guiding*, meaning that the difference in refractive index between the core and the cladding is very small (typically less than 1%).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Light travels through the fiber core, bouncing back and forth off the boundary between the core and cladding.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Because the light must strike the boundary with an angle greater than the critical angle, only light that enters the fiber within a certain range of angles can travel down the fiber without leaking out.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This range of angles is called the acceptance cone of the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] There is a maximum angle from the fiber axis at which light may enter the fiber so that it will propagate, or travel, in the core of the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The sine of this maximum angle is the numerical aperture (NA) of the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber with a larger NA requires less precision to splice and work with than fiber with a smaller NA.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The size of this acceptance cone is a function of the refractive index difference between the fiber's core and cladding.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers with a large core diameter (greater than 10 micrometers) may be analyzed by geometrical optics.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Such fibers are called *multi-mode fibers*, from the electromagnetic analysis (see below).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In a step-index multi-mode fiber, rays of light are guided along the fiber core by total internal reflection.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Rays that meet the core-cladding boundary at an angle (measured relative to a line normal to the boundary) greater than the critical angle for this boundary, are completely reflected.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The critical angle is determined by the difference in the index of refraction between the core and cladding materials.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Rays that meet the boundary at a low angle are refracted from the core into the cladding where they terminate.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The critical angle determines the acceptance angle of the fiber, often reported as a numerical aperture.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] A high numerical aperture allows light to propagate down the fiber in rays both close to the axis and at various angles, allowing efficient coupling of light into the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] However, this high numerical aperture increases the amount of dispersion as rays at different angles have different path lengths and therefore take different amounts of time to traverse the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In graded-index fiber, the index of refraction in the core decreases continuously between the axis and the cladding.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This causes light rays to bend smoothly as they approach the cladding, rather than reflecting abruptly from the core-cladding boundary.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The resulting curved paths reduce multi-path dispersion because high-angle rays pass more through the lower-index periphery of the core, rather than the high-index center.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The index profile is chosen to minimize the difference in axial propagation speeds of the various rays in the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This ideal index profile is very close to a parabolic relationship between the index and the distance from the axis.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers with a core diameter less than about ten times the wavelength of the propagating light cannot be modeled using geometric optics.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Instead, they must be analyzed as an electromagnetic waveguide structure, according to Maxwell's equations as reduced to the electromagnetic wave equation.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] As an optical waveguide, the fiber supports one or more confined transverse modes by which light can propagate along the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber supporting only one mode is called *single-mode*.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The waveguide analysis shows that the light energy in the fiber is not completely confined in the core.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Instead, especially in single-mode fibers, a significant fraction of the energy in the bound mode travels in the cladding as an evanescent wave.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The most common type of single-mode fiber has a core diameter of 8–10 micrometers and is designed for use in the near infrared.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Multi-mode fiber, by comparison, is manufactured with core diameters as small as 50 micrometers and as large as hundreds of micrometers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Some special-purpose optical fiber is constructed with a non-cylindrical core or cladding layer, usually with an elliptical or rectangular cross-section.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] These include polarization-maintaining fiber used in fiber optic sensors and fiber designed to suppress whispering gallery mode propagation.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Photonic-crystal fiber is made with a regular pattern of index variation (often in the form of cylindrical holes that run along the length of the fiber).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Such fiber uses diffraction effects instead of or in addition to total internal reflection, to confine light to the fiber's core.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The properties of the fiber can be tailored to a wide variety of applications.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation in fiber optics, also known as transmission loss, is the reduction in the intensity of the light signal as it travels through the transmission medium.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation coefficients in fiber optics are usually expressed in units of dB/km.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The medium is usually a fiber of silica glass that confines the incident light beam within.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation is an important factor limiting the transmission of a digital signal across large distances.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Thus, much research has gone into both limiting the attenuation and maximizing the amplification of the optical signal.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Single-mode optical fibers can be made with extremely low loss.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Corning's Vascade® EX2500 fiber, a low loss single-mode fiber for telecommunications wavelengths, has a nominal attenuation of 0.148 dB/km at 1550 nm.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] A 10 km length of such fiber transmits nearly 71% of optical energy at 1550 nm.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation in optical fiber is caused primarily by both scattering and absorption.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In fibers based on fluoride glasses such as ZBLAN, minimum attenuation is limited by impurity absorption.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The vast majority of optical fibers are based on silica glass, where impurity absorption is negligible.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In silica fibers attenuation is determined by intrinsic mechanisms: Rayleigh scattering and infrared absorption in the glasses through which the light is propagating.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Absorption in silica increases steeply at wavelengths above 1570 nm.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] At wavelengths most useful for telecommunications, Rayleigh scattering is the dominant loss mechanism.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] At 1550 nm attenuation components for a record low loss fiber are given as follows: Rayleigh scattering loss: 0.1200 dB/km, infrared absorption loss: 0.0150 dB/km, impurity absorption loss: 0.0047 dB/km, waveguide imperfection loss: 0.0010 dB/km.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The propagation of light through the core of an optical fiber is based on the total internal reflection of the lightwave, in terms of geometric optics, or guided modes, in terms of electromagnetic waveguide.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In a typical single mode optical fiber about 75% of light is propagating through the core material, having higher refractive index, and about 25% of light is propagating through the cladding, having lower refractive index.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The interface between the core and cladding glasses is exceptionally smooth and does not give rise to a significant scattering loss or a waveguide imperfection loss.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The scattering loss originates primarily from the Rayleigh scattering in the bulk of the glasses composing the fiber core and cladding.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The scattering of light in optical quality glass fiber is caused by molecular level irregularities (compositional fluctuations) in the glass structure.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Indeed, one emerging school of thought is that glass is simply the limiting case of a polycrystalline solid.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Within this framework, *domains* exhibiting various degrees of short-range order become the building blocks of metals as well as glasses and ceramics.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Distributed both between and within these domains are micro-structural defects that provide the most ideal locations for light scattering.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Scattering depends on the wavelength of the light being scattered and on the size of the scattering centers.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Angular dependence of the light intensity scattered from an optical fiber matched that of Rayleigh scattering, indicating that the scattering centers are much smaller than the wavelength of propagating light.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] It originates from the density fluctuations driven by fictive temperature of the glass, and from the concentration fluctuations of dopants in both the core and the cladding.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Rayleigh scattering coefficient, *R*, can be presented as : $R=R_{\text{d}}+R_{\text{c}}$ where *R*d represents Rayleigh scattering on density fluctuations and *R*c represents Rayleigh scattering on dopant concentration fluctuations.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The only physically significant variable affecting scattering on density fluctuations is the fictive temperature of the glass, lower fictive temperature results in a more homogeneous glass and lower Rayleigh scattering.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Fictive temperature may be dramatically reduced by about 100 wt. ppm of alkali oxide dopant in the fiber core, as well as slower cooling of the fiber during the fiber draw process.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] These approaches are used to produce optical fibers with the lowest attenuation, especially those for submarine telecom cables.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] For small dopant concentrations, *R*c is proportional to *x*(d*n*/d*x*)2, where x is the mole fraction of the dopant in SiO2-based glass and n is the refractive index of the glass.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] When GeO2 dopant is used to increase the refractive index of the fiber core, it increases the concentration fluctuation component of Rayleigh scattering, and attenuation of the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This is why the lowest attenuation fibers do not use GeO2 in the core, and use fluorine in the cladding, to reduce the refractive index of the cladding.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] *R*c in pure silica core fiber is proportional to the overlap integral between LP01 mode and fluorine-induced concentration fluctuation component in the cladding.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In the core of potassium-doped pure silica-core (KPSC) fiber only density fluctuations play a significant role, as the concentrations of K2O, fluorine and chlorine are very low.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The density fluctuations in the core are moderated by lower fictive temperature resulting from potassium doping, and are further reduced by annealing during the fiber draw process.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] This differs from the cladding, where higher fluorine dopant levels and the resulting concentration fluctuations add to the loss.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In such fibers the light travelling through the core experiences lower scattering and lower attenuation compared to the light propagating through the cladding segment of the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] At high optical powers, scattering can also be caused by nonlinear optical processes in the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In addition to light scattering, attenuation or signal loss can also occur due to selective absorption of specific wavelengths.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The design of any optically transparent device requires the selection of materials based upon knowledge of its properties and limitations.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The crystal structure absorption characteristics observed at the lower frequency regions (mid- to far-IR wavelength range) define the long-wavelength transparency limit of the material.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] They are the result of the interactive coupling between the motions of thermally induced vibrations of the constituent atoms and molecules of the solid lattice and the incident light wave radiation.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Hence, all materials are bounded by limiting regions of absorption caused by atomic and molecular vibrations (bond-stretching) in the far-infrared (>10 μm).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] In other words, the selective absorption of IR light by a particular material occurs because the selected frequency of the light wave matches the frequency (or an integer multiple of the frequency, i.e. harmonic) at which the particles of that material vibrate.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Since different atoms and molecules have different natural frequencies of vibration, they will selectively absorb different frequencies (or portions of the spectrum) of IR light.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Reflection and transmission of light waves occur because the frequencies of the light waves do not match the natural resonant frequencies of vibration of the objects.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] When IR light of these frequencies strikes an object, the energy is either reflected or transmitted.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation over a cable run is significantly increased by the inclusion of connectors and splices.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Connectors typically introduce 0.3 dB per connector on well-polished connectors.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] Splices typically introduce less than 0.2 dB per splice.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] where the dB loss per kilometer is a function of the type of fiber and can be found in the manufacturer's specifications.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] For example, a typical 1550 nm single-mode fiber has a loss of 0.3 dB per kilometer.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p01] The calculated loss budget is used when testing to confirm that the measured loss is within the normal operating parameters.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Glass optical fibers are almost always made from silica, but some other materials, such as fluorozirconate, fluoroaluminate, and chalcogenide glasses as well as crystalline materials like sapphire, are used for longer-wavelength infrared or other specialized applications.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Silica and fluoride glasses usually have refractive indices of about 1.5, but some materials such as the chalcogenides can have indices as high as 3.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Typically the index difference between core and cladding is less than one percent.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Plastic optical fibers (POF) are commonly step-index multi-mode fibers with a core diameter of 0.5 millimeters or larger.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] POF typically have higher attenuation coefficients than glass fibers, 1 dB/m or higher, and this high attenuation limits the range of POF-based systems.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Silica exhibits fairly good optical transmission over a wide range of wavelengths.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In the near-infrared (near IR) portion of the spectrum, particularly around 1.5 μm, silica can have extremely low absorption and scattering losses of the order of 0.2 dB/km.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Such low losses depend on using ultra-pure silica.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] A high transparency in the 1.4-μm region is achieved by maintaining a low concentration of hydroxyl groups (OH).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Alternatively, a high OH concentration is better for transmission in the ultraviolet (UV) region.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Silica can be drawn into fibers at reasonably high temperatures and has a fairly broad glass transformation range.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] One other advantage is that fusion splicing and cleaving of silica fibers is relatively effective.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Silica fiber also has high mechanical strength against both pulling and even bending, provided that the fiber is not too thick and that the surfaces have been well prepared during processing.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Even simple cleaving of the ends of the fiber can provide nicely flat surfaces with acceptable optical quality.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Silica is also relatively chemically inert.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In particular, it is not hygroscopic (does not absorb water).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Silica glass can be doped with various materials.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] One purpose of doping is to raise the refractive index (e.g. with germanium dioxide (GeO2) or aluminium oxide (Al2O3)) or to lower it (e.g. with fluorine or boron trioxide (B2O3)).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Doping is also possible with laser-active ions (for example, rare-earth-doped fibers) in order to obtain active fibers to be used, for example, in fiber amplifiers or laser applications.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Both the fiber core and cladding are typically doped, so that the entire assembly (core and cladding) is effectively the same compound (e.g. an aluminosilicate, germanosilicate, phosphosilicate or borosilicate glass).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Particularly for active fibers, pure silica is usually not a very suitable host glass, because it exhibits a low solubility for rare-earth ions.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] This can lead to quenching effects due to the clustering of dopant ions.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Aluminosilicates are much more effective in this respect.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Silica fiber also exhibits a high threshold for optical damage.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] This property ensures a low tendency for laser-induced breakdown.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] This is important for fiber amplifiers when utilized for the amplification of short pulses.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Because of these properties, silica fibers are the material of choice in many optical applications, such as communications (except for very short distances with plastic optical fiber), fiber lasers, fiber amplifiers, and fiber-optic sensors.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Large efforts put forth in the development of various types of silica fibers have further increased the performance of such fibers over other materials.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Fluoride glass is a class of non-oxide optical quality glasses composed of fluorides of various metals.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Because of the low viscosity of these glasses, it is very difficult to completely avoid crystallization while processing it through the glass transition (or drawing the fiber from the melt).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Thus, although heavy metal fluoride glasses (HMFG) exhibit very low optical attenuation, they are not only difficult to manufacture, but are quite fragile, and have poor resistance to moisture and other environmental attacks.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Their best attribute is that they lack the absorption band associated with the hydroxyl (OH) group (3,200–3,600 cm−1; i.e., 2,777–3,125 nm or 2.78–3.13 μm), which is present in nearly all oxide-based glasses.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Such low losses were never realized in practice, and the fragility and high cost of fluoride fibers made them less than ideal as primary candidates.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Fluoride fibers are used in mid-IR spectroscopy, fiber optic sensors, thermometry, and imaging.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Fluoride fibers can be used for guided lightwave transmission in media such as YAG (yttrium aluminium garnet) lasers at 2.9 μm, as required for medical applications (e.g. ophthalmology and dentistry).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] An example of a heavy metal fluoride glass is the ZBLAN glass group, composed of zirconium, barium, lanthanum, aluminium, and sodium fluorides.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Their main technological application is as optical waveguides in both planar and fiber forms.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] They are advantageous especially in the mid-infrared (2,000–5,000 nm) range.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Phosphate glass is a class of optical glasses composed of metaphosphates of various metals.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Instead of the SiO4 tetrahedra in the network solid structure of silicate glasses, the building block for this glass is phosphorus pentoxide (P2O5), which crystallizes in at least four different forms.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The most familiar polymorph is the cagelike structure of P4O10.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Phosphate glasses can be advantageous over silica glasses for optical fibers with a high concentration of doping rare-earth ions.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] A mix of fluoride glass and phosphate glass is fluorophosphate glass.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The chalcogens—the elements in group 16 of the periodic table—particularly sulfur (S), selenium (Se) and tellurium (Te)—react with more electropositive elements, such as silver, to form chalcogenides.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] These are extremely versatile compounds, in that they can be crystalline or amorphous, metallic or semiconducting, and conductors of ions or electrons.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Chalcogenide glass can be used to make fibers for far infrared transmission.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Standard optical fibers are made by first constructing a large-diameter *preform* with a carefully controlled refractive index profile, and then *pulling* the preform to form the long, thin optical fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The preform is commonly made by three chemical vapor deposition methods: *inside vapor deposition*, *outside vapor deposition*, and *vapor axial deposition*.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] With *inside vapor deposition*, the preform starts as a hollow glass tube approximately 40 centimeters (16 in) long, which is placed horizontally and rotated slowly on a lathe.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Gases such as silicon tetrachloride (SiCl4) or germanium tetrachloride (GeCl4) are injected with oxygen in the end of the tube.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The gases are then heated by means of an external hydrogen burner, bringing the temperature of the gas up to 1,900 K (1,600 °C, 3,000 °F), where the tetrachlorides react with oxygen to produce silica or germanium dioxide particles.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] When the reaction conditions are chosen to allow this reaction to occur in the gas phase throughout the tube volume, in contrast to earlier techniques where the reaction occurred only on the glass surface, this technique is called *modified chemical vapor deposition*.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The oxide particles then agglomerate to form large particle chains, which subsequently deposit on the walls of the tube as soot.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The deposition is due to the large difference in temperature between the gas core and the wall causing the gas to push the particles outward in a process known as thermophoresis.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The torch is then traversed up and down the length of the tube to deposit the material evenly.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] After the torch has reached the end of the tube, it is then brought back to the beginning of the tube and the deposited particles are then melted to form a solid layer.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] This process is repeated until a sufficient amount of material has been deposited.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] For each layer the composition can be modified by varying the gas composition, resulting in precise control of the finished fiber's optical properties.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In outside vapor deposition or vapor axial deposition, the glass is formed by *flame hydrolysis*, a reaction in which silicon tetrachloride and germanium tetrachloride are oxidized by reaction with water in an oxyhydrogen flame.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In outside vapor deposition, the glass is deposited onto a solid rod, which is removed before further processing.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In vapor axial deposition, a short *seed rod* is used, and a porous preform, whose length is not limited by the size of the source rod, is built up on its end.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The porous preform is consolidated into a transparent, solid preform by heating to about 1,800 K (1,500 °C, 2,800 °F).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Typical communications fiber uses a circular preform.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] For some applications such as double-clad fibers another form is preferred.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In fiber lasers based on double-clad fiber, an asymmetric shape improves the filling factor for laser pumping.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Because of the surface tension, the shape is smoothed during the drawing process, and the shape of the resulting fiber does not reproduce the sharp edges of the preform.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Nevertheless, careful polishing of the preform is important, since any defects of the preform surface affect the optical and mechanical properties of the resulting fiber.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The preform, regardless of construction, is placed in a device known as a drawing tower, where the preform tip is heated and the optical fiber is pulled out as a string.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The tension on the fiber can be controlled to maintain the desired fiber thickness.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The light is guided down the core of the fiber by an optical cladding with a lower refractive index that traps light in the core through total internal reflection.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] For some types of fiber, the cladding is made of glass and is drawn along with the core from a preform with radially varying index of refraction.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] For other types of fiber, the cladding is made of plastic and is applied like a coating (see below).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The cladding is coated by a buffer, (not to be confused with an actual buffer tube), that protects it from moisture and physical damage.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] These coatings are UV-cured urethane acrylate composite or polyimide materials applied to the outside of the fiber during the drawing process.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The coatings protect the very delicate strands of glass fiber—about the size of a human hair—and allow it to survive the rigors of manufacturing, proof testing, cabling, and installation.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The buffer coating must be stripped off the fiber for termination or splicing.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Today's glass optical fiber draw processes employ a dual-layer coating approach.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] An inner primary coating is designed to act as a shock absorber to minimize attenuation caused by microbending.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] An outer secondary coating protects the primary coating against mechanical damage and acts as a barrier to lateral forces, and may be colored to differentiate strands in bundled cable constructions.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] These fiber optic coating layers are applied during the fiber draw, at speeds approaching 100 kilometers per hour (60 mph).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Fiber optic coatings are applied using one of two methods: *wet-on-dry* and *wet-on-wet*.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In wet-on-dry, the fiber passes through a primary coating application, which is then UV cured, then through the secondary coating application, which is subsequently cured.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In wet-on-wet, the fiber passes through both the primary and secondary coating applications, then goes to UV curing.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The thickness of the coating is taken into account when calculating the stress that the fiber experiences under different bend configurations.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In a two-point bend configuration, a coated fiber is bent in a U-shape and placed between the grooves of two faceplates, which are brought together until the fiber breaks.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The stress in the fiber in this configuration is given by $\sigma =1.198E{d_{\text{f}} \over d-d_{\text{c}}},$ where d is the distance between the faceplates.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The coefficient 1.198 is a geometric constant associated with this configuration.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Fiber optic coatings protect the glass fibers from scratches that could lead to strength degradation.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The combination of moisture and scratches accelerates the aging and deterioration of fiber strength.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] When fiber is subjected to low stresses over a long period, fiber fatigue can occur.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Over time or in extreme conditions, these factors combine to cause microscopic flaws in the glass fiber to propagate, which can ultimately result in fiber failure.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Three key characteristics of fiber optic waveguides can be affected by environmental conditions: strength, attenuation, and resistance to losses caused by microbending.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] External optical fiber cable jackets and buffer tubes protect glass optical fiber from environmental conditions that can affect the fiber's performance and long-term durability.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] On the inside, coatings ensure the reliability of the signal being carried and help minimize attenuation due to microbending.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In practical fibers, the cladding is usually coated with a tough resin and features an additional *buffer* layer, which may be further surrounded by a *jacket* layer, usually plastic.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] These layers add strength to the fiber but do not affect its optical properties.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Rigid fiber assemblies sometimes put light-absorbing glass between the fibers, to prevent light that leaks out of one fiber from entering another.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] This reduces crosstalk between the fibers, or reduces flare in fiber bundle imaging applications.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Multi-fiber cable usually uses colored buffers to identify each strand.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Modern cables come in a wide variety of sheathings and armor, designed for applications such as direct burial in trenches, high voltage isolation, dual use as power lines, installation in conduit, lashing to aerial telephone poles, submarine installation, and insertion in paved streets.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Some fiber optic cable versions are reinforced with aramid yarns or glass yarns as an intermediary strength member.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In commercial terms, usage of the glass yarns are more cost-effective with no loss of mechanical durability.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Glass yarns also protect the cable core against rodents and termites.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Fiber cable can be very flexible, but traditional fiber's loss increases greatly if the fiber is bent with a radius smaller than around 30 mm.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] This creates a problem when the cable is bent around corners.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] *Bendable fibers*, targeted toward easier installation in home environments, have been standardized as ITU-T G.657.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] This type of fiber can be bent with a radius as low as 7.5 mm without adverse impact.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Even more bendable fibers have been developed.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Bendable fiber may also be resistant to fiber hacking, in which the signal in a fiber is surreptitiously monitored by bending the fiber and detecting the leakage.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Another important feature of cable is cable's ability to withstand tension which determines how much force can be applied to the cable during installation.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Optical fibers are connected to terminal equipment by optical fiber connectors.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] These connectors are usually of a standard type such as *FC*, *SC*, *ST*, *LC*, *MTRJ*, *MPO* or *SMA*.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Optical fibers may be connected by connectors typically on a patch panel, or permanently by splicing, that is, joining two fibers together to form a continuous optical waveguide.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The generally accepted splicing method is fusion splicing, which melts the fiber ends together.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] For quicker fastening jobs, a *mechanical splice* is used.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] All splicing techniques involve installing an enclosure that protects the splice.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Fusion splicing is done with a specialized instrument.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The fiber ends are first stripped of their protective polymer coating (as well as the more sturdy outer jacket, if present).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The ends are cleaved with a precision cleaver to make them perpendicular, and are placed into special holders in the fusion splicer.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The splice is usually inspected via a magnified viewing screen to check the cleaves before and fusion after the splice.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The splicer uses small motors to align the end faces together, and emits a small spark between electrodes at the gap to burn off dust and moisture.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Then the splicer generates a larger spark that raises the temperature above the melting point of the glass, fusing the ends permanently.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The location and energy of the spark is carefully controlled so that the molten core and cladding do not mix, and this minimizes optical loss.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] A splice loss estimate is measured by the splicer by directing light through the cladding on one side and measuring the light leaking from the cladding on the other side.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The complexity of this process makes fiber splicing much more difficult than splicing copper wire.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Mechanical fiber splices are designed to be quicker and easier to install, but there is still the need for stripping, careful cleaning, and precision cleaving.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The fiber ends are aligned and held together by a precision sleeve, often using a clear index-matching gel that enhances the transmission of light across the joint.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Mechanical splices typically have a higher optical loss and are less robust than fusion splices, especially if the gel is used.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Fibers are terminated in connectors that hold the fiber end precisely and securely.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] An optical fiber connector is a rigid cylindrical barrel surrounded by a sleeve that holds the barrel in its mating socket.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The mating mechanism can be *push and click*, *turn and latch* (*bayonet mount*), or *screw-in* (*threaded*).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The barrel is typically free to move within the sleeve and may have a key that prevents the barrel and fiber from rotating as the connectors are mated.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] A typical connector is installed by preparing the fiber end and inserting it into the rear of the connector body.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Quick-set adhesive is usually used to hold the fiber securely, and a strain relief is secured to the rear.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Once the adhesive sets, the fiber's end is polished.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Various polish profiles are used, depending on the type of fiber and the application.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The resulting signal strength loss is called *gap loss*.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] For single-mode fiber, fiber ends are typically polished with a slight curvature that makes the mated connectors touch only at their cores.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] This is called a *physical contact* (PC) polish.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The curved surface may be polished at an angle, to make an *angled physical contact (APC)* connection.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Such connections have higher loss than PC connections but greatly reduced back reflection because light that reflects from the angled surface leaks out of the fiber core.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] APC fiber ends have low back reflection even when disconnected.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In the 1990s, the number of parts per connector, polishing of the fibers, and the need to oven-bake the epoxy in each connector made terminating fiber optic cables difficult.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Today, connector types on the market offer easier, less labor-intensive ways of terminating cables.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Some of the most popular connectors are pre-polished at the factory and include a gel inside the connector.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] A cleave is made at a required length, to get as close to the polished piece already inside the connector.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The gel surrounds the point where the two pieces meet inside the connector for very little light loss.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] For the most demanding installations, factory pre-polished pigtails of sufficient length to reach the first fusion splice enclosure assures good performance and minimizes on-site labor.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] It is often necessary to align an optical fiber with another optical fiber or with an optoelectronic device such as a light-emitting diode, a laser diode, or a modulator.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] This can involve either carefully aligning the fiber and placing it in contact with the device, or can use a lens to allow coupling over an air gap.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Typically the size of the fiber mode is much larger than the size of the mode in a laser diode or a silicon optical chip.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In this case, a tapered or lensed fiber is used to match the fiber mode field distribution to that of the other element.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The lens on the end of the fiber can be formed using polishing, laser cutting or fusion splicing.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In a laboratory environment, a bare fiber end is coupled using a fiber launch system, which uses a microscope objective lens to focus the light down to a fine point.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] A precision translation stage (micro-positioning table) is used to move the lens, fiber, or device to allow the coupling efficiency to be optimized.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Fibers with a connector on the end make this process much simpler: the connector is simply plugged into a pre-aligned fiber-optic collimator, which contains a lens that is either accurately positioned to the fiber or is adjustable.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] To achieve the best injection efficiency into a single-mode fiber, the direction, position, size, and divergence of the beam must all be optimized.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] With good optimization, 70 to 90% coupling efficiency can be achieved.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] With properly polished single-mode fibers, the emitted beam has an almost perfect Gaussian shape—even in the far field—if a good lens is used.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The lens needs to be large enough to support the full numerical aperture of the fiber, and must not introduce aberrations in the beam.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] At optical intensities above two megawatts per square centimeter, when a fiber is subjected to a shock or is otherwise suddenly damaged, a *fiber fuse* can occur.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The reflection from the damage vaporizes the fiber immediately before the break, and this new defect remains reflective so that the damage propagates back toward the transmitter at 1–3 meters per second (4–11 km/h, 2–8 mph).
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The open fiber control system, which ensures laser eye safety in the event of a broken fiber, can also effectively halt propagation of the fiber fuse.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] In situations, such as undersea cables, where high power levels might be used without the need for open fiber control, a fiber fuse protection device at the transmitter can break the circuit to minimize damage.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] The refractive index of fibers varies slightly with the frequency of light, and light sources are not perfectly monochromatic.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Chromatic dispersion arises from both the waveguide structure of the fiber and the dispersive properties of the glass itself, with the latter contribution typically being dominant.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] Modulation of the light source to transmit a signal also slightly widens the frequency band of the transmitted light.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] This has the effect that, over long distances and at high modulation speeds, different portions of light can take different times to arrive at the receiver, ultimately making the signal impossible to discern.
[src:optical-networking/optical-fiber-p02] This problem can be overcome in several ways, including the use of extra repeaters and the use of a relatively short length of fiber that has the opposite refractive index gradient.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] An **optical transport network** (**OTN**) is a digital wrapper that encapsulates frames of data, to allow multiple data sources to be sent on the same channel.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] This creates an optical virtual private network for each client signal.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] ITU-T defines an optical transport network as a set of optical network elements (ONE) connected by optical fiber links, able to provide functionality of transport, multiplexing, switching, management, supervision and survivability of optical channels carrying client signals.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] An ONE may re-time, re-Amplify, re-shape (3R) but it does not have to be 3R – it can be purely photonic.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] Unless connected by optical fibre links, it shall not be OTN.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] Mere functionality of switching, management, supervision shall not make it OTN, unless the signals are carried through optical fibre.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] Unlike SONET/SDH, OTN provides a mechanism to manage multiplexed wavelengths in a DWDM system.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] OTN was designed to provide higher throughput (currently 400G) than its predecessor SONET/SDH, which stops at 40 Gbit/s, per channel.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] ITU-T Recommendation G.709 is commonly called Optical Transport Network (OTN) (also called **digital wrapper technology** or **optical channel wrapper**).
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] As of December 2009, OTN has standardized the following line rates.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] (LAN) PHY coming from IP/Ethernet switches and routers at full line rate (10.3 Gbit/s).
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] develop for transport of 10G LAN PHY, and one for 10G WAN PHY, over SDH and OTN.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] The OTUk (k=1/2/2e/3/3e2/4) is an information structure into which another information structure called ODUk (k=1/2/2e/3/3e2/4) is mapped.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] The ODUk signal is the server layer signal for client signals.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] The OTN signals at all data-rates have the same frame structure but the frame period reduces as the data-rate increases.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] As a result, the Time-Slot Interchange (TSI) technique of implementing SONET/SDH switch fabrics is not directly applicable to OTN switch fabrics.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] OTN switch fabrics are typically implemented using Packet Switch Fabrics.
[src:optical-networking/optical-transport-network] On a point-to-point OTN link there is latency due to forward error correction (FEC) processing.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In fiber-optic communications, **wavelength-division multiplexing** (**WDM**) is a technology which multiplexes a number of optical carrier signals onto a single optical fiber by using different wavelengths (i.e., colors) of laser light.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This technique enables bidirectional communications over a single strand of fiber (also called **wavelength-division duplexing**) as well as multiplication of capacity.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The term WDM is commonly applied to an optical carrier, which is typically described by its wavelength, whereas frequency-division multiplexing typically applies to a radio carrier, more often described by frequency.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is purely conventional because wavelength and frequency communicate the same information.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Specifically, frequency (in Hertz, which is cycles per second) multiplied by wavelength (the physical length of one cycle) equals the velocity of the carrier wave.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In a vacuum, this is the speed of light (usually denoted by the lowercase letter, c).
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In glass fiber, velocity is substantially slower - usually about 0.7 times c.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The data rate in practical systems is a fraction of the carrier frequency.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] A WDM system uses a multiplexer at the transmitter to join the several signals together and a demultiplexer at the receiver to split them apart.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] With the right type of fiber, it is possible to have a device that does both simultaneously and can function as an optical add-drop multiplexer.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The optical filtering devices used have conventionally been etalons (stable solid-state single-frequency Fabry–Pérot interferometers in the form of thin-film-coated optical glass).
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] As there are three different WDM types, whereof one is called *WDM*, the notation *xWDM* is normally used when discussing the technology as such.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The concept was first published in 1970 by Delange, and by 1980 WDM systems were being realized in the laboratory.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The first WDM systems combined only two signals.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Modern systems can handle 160 signals and can thus expand a basic 100 Gbit/s system over a single fiber pair to over 16 Tbit/s.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM systems are popular with telecommunications companies because they allow them to expand the capacity of the network without laying more fiber.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] By using WDM and optical amplifiers, they can accommodate several generations of technology development in their optical infrastructure without having to overhaul the backbone network.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The capacity of a given link can be expanded simply by upgrading the multiplexers and demultiplexers at each end.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is often done by the use of optical-to-electrical-to-optical (O/E/O) translation at the very edge of the transport network, thus permitting interoperation with existing equipment with optical interfaces.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Most WDM systems operate on single-mode optical fiber cables which have a core diameter of 9 μm.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Certain forms of WDM can also be used in multi-mode optical fiber cables (also known as premises cables) which have core diameters of 50 or 62.5 μm.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Early WDM systems were expensive and complicated to run.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] However, recent standardization and a better understanding of the dynamics of WDM systems have made WDM less expensive to deploy.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Optical receivers, in contrast to laser sources, tend to be wideband devices.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Therefore, the demultiplexer must provide the wavelength selectivity of the receiver in the WDM system.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM systems are divided into three different wavelength patterns: **normal** (WDM), **coarse** (CWDM) and **dense** (DWDM).
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Normal WDM (sometimes called BWDM) uses the two normal wavelengths 1310 and 1550 nm on one fiber.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Coarse WDM provides up to 16 channels across multiple transmission windows of silica fibers.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] *Dense WDM* (DWDM) uses the C-Band (1530 nm-1565 nm) transmission window but with denser channel spacing.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Channel plans vary, but a typical DWDM system would use 40 channels at 100 GHz spacing or 80 channels with 50 GHz spacing.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Some technologies are capable of 12.5 GHz spacing (sometimes called ultra-dense WDM).
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] New amplification options (Raman amplification) enable the extension of the usable wavelengths to the L-band (1565–1625 nm), more or less doubling these numbers.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Coarse wavelength-division multiplexing (CWDM), in contrast to DWDM, uses increased channel spacing to allow less sophisticated and thus cheaper transceiver designs.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] To provide 16 channels on a single fiber, CWDM uses the entire frequency band spanning the second and third transmission windows (1310/1550 nm respectively) including the critical frequencies where OH scattering may occur.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] OH-free silica fibers are recommended if the wavelengths between the second and third transmission windows are to be used.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Avoiding this region, the channels 47, 49, 51, 53, 55, 57, 59, 61 remain and these are the most commonly used.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] With OS2 fibers the water peak problem is overcome, and all possible 18 channels can be used.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM, CWDM and DWDM are based on the same concept of using multiple wavelengths of light on a single fiber but differ in the spacing of the wavelengths, number of channels, and the ability to amplify the multiplexed signals in the optical space.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Erbium-doped optical fiber amplifiers (EDFAs) provide an efficient wideband amplification for the C-band, Raman amplification adds a mechanism for amplification in the L-band.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] For CWDM, wideband optical amplification is not available, limiting the optical spans to several tens of kilometers.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Originally, the term *coarse wavelength-division multiplexing* (CWDM) was fairly generic and described a number of different channel configurations.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In general, the choice of channel spacings and frequency in these configurations precluded the use of EDFAs.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Prior to the relatively recent ITU standardization of the term, one common definition for CWDM was two or more signals multiplexed onto a single fiber, with one signal in the 1550 nm band and the other in the 1310 nm band.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In 2002, the ITU standardized a channel spacing grid for CWDM (ITU-T G.694.2) using the wavelengths from 1270 nm through 1610 nm with a channel spacing of 20 nm.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] ITU G.694.2 was revised in 2003 to shift the channel centers by 1 nm so, strictly speaking, the center wavelengths are 1271 to 1611 nm.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Many CWDM wavelengths below 1470 nm are considered unusable on older G.652 specification fibers, due to the increased attenuation in the 1270–1470 nm bands.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Newer fibers which conform to the G.652.C and G.652.D standards, such as Corning SMF-28e and Samsung Widepass, nearly eliminate the water-related attenuation peak at 1383 nm and allow for full operation of all 18 ITU CWDM channels in metropolitan networks.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The main characteristic of the recent ITU CWDM standard is that the signals are not spaced appropriately for amplification by EDFAs.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This limits the total CWDM optical span to somewhere near 60 km for a 2.5 Gbit/s signal, suitable for use in metropolitan applications.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The relaxed optical frequency stabilization requirements allow the associated costs of CWDM to approach those of non-WDM optical components.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] CWDM is being used in cable television networks, where different wavelengths are used for the *downstream* and *upstream* signals.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In these systems, the wavelengths used are often widely separated.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] For example, the downstream signal might be at 1310 nm while the upstream signal is at 1550 nm.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The 10GBASE-LX4 10 Gbit/s physical layer standard is an example of a CWDM system in which four wavelengths near 1310 nm, each carrying a 3.125 Gbit/s data stream, are used to carry 10 Gbit/s of aggregate data.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Passive CWDM is an implementation of CWDM that uses no electrical power.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] It separates the wavelengths using passive optical components such as bandpass filters and prisms.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Many manufacturers are promoting passive CWDM to deploy fiber to the home.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] An **intermediate line repeater** is placed approximately every 80–100 km to compensate for the loss of optical power as the signal travels along the fiber.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The 'multi-wavelength optical signal' is amplified by an EDFA, which usually consists of several amplifier stages.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] An **intermediate optical terminal**, or **optical add-drop multiplexer (OADM)**.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is a remote amplification site that amplifies the multi-wavelength signal that may have traversed up to 140 km or more before reaching the remote site.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Optical diagnostics and telemetry are often extracted or inserted at such a site to allow for localization of any fiber breaks or signal impairments.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In more sophisticated systems (which are no longer point-to-point), several signals out of the multi-wavelength optical signal may be removed and dropped locally.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] At the remote site, the terminal de-multiplexer consisting of an optical de-multiplexer and one or more wavelength-converting transponders separates the multi-wavelength optical signal back into individual data signals and outputs them on separate fibers for client-layer systems (such as SONET/SDH).
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Originally, this de-multiplexing was performed entirely passively, except for some telemetry, as most SONET systems can receive 1,550 nm signals.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] However, in order to allow for transmission to remote client-layer systems (and to allow for digital domain signal integrity determination) such de-multiplexed signals are usually sent to O/E/O output transponders prior to being relayed to their client-layer systems.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Often, the functionality of the output transponder has been integrated into that of the input transponder, so that most commercial systems have transponders that support bi-directional interfaces on both their 1,550 nm (i.e., internal) side, and external (i.e., client-facing) side.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Transponders in some systems supporting 40 GHz nominal operation may also perform forward error correction (FEC) via digital wrapper technology, as described in the ITU-T G.709 standard.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is data channel that uses an additional wavelength usually outside the EDFA amplification band (at 1,510 nm, 1,620 nm, 1,310 nm or another proprietary wavelength).
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The OSC carries information about the multi-wavelength optical signal as well as remote conditions at the optical terminal or EDFA site.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] It is also normally used for remote software upgrades and user (i.e., network operator) Network Management information.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] It is the multi-wavelength analog to SONET's DCC (or supervisory channel).
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] ITU standards suggest that the OSC should utilize an OC-3 signal structure, though some vendors have opted to use Fast Ethernet or another signal format.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Unlike the 1550 nm multi-wavelength signal containing client data, the OSC is always terminated at intermediate amplifier sites, where it receives local information before re-transmission.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The introduction of the ITU-T G.694.1 frequency grid in 2002 has made it easier to integrate WDM with older but more standard SONET/SDH systems.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM wavelengths are positioned in a grid having exactly 100 GHz (about 0.8 nm) spacing in optical frequency, with a reference frequency fixed at 193.10 THz (1,552.52 nm).
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The main grid is placed inside the optical fiber amplifier bandwidth, but can be extended to wider bandwidths.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The first commercial deployment of DWDM was made by Ciena Corporation on the Sprint network in June 1996.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Today's DWDM systems use 50 GHz or even 25 GHz channel spacing for up to 160 channel operation.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] DWDM systems have to maintain more stable wavelength or frequency than those needed for CWDM because of the closer spacing of the wavelengths.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Precision temperature control of the laser transmitter is required in DWDM systems to prevent drift off a very narrow frequency window of the order of a few GHz.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] These factors of smaller volume and higher performance result in DWDM systems typically being more expensive than CWDM.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Recent innovations in DWDM transport systems include pluggable and software-tunable transceiver modules capable of operating on 40 or 80 channels.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This dramatically reduces the need for discrete spare pluggable modules, when a handful of pluggable devices can handle the full range of wavelengths.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Wavelength-converting transponders originally translated the transmit wavelength of a client-layer signal into one of the DWDM system's internal wavelengths in the 1,550 nm band.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] External wavelengths in the 1,550 nm most likely need to be translated, as they almost certainly do not have the required frequency stability tolerances nor the optical power necessary for the system's EDFA.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In the mid-1990s, however, wavelength-converting transponders rapidly took on the additional function of signal regeneration.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Signal regeneration in transponders quickly evolved through 1R to 2R to 3R and into overhead-monitoring multi-bitrate 3R regenerators.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] of the received optical signal, with little signal cleanup occurring.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This limited the reach of early DWDM systems because the signal had to be handed off to a client-layer receiver (likely from a different vendor) before the signal deteriorated too far.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Signal monitoring was basically confined to optical domain parameters such as received power.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Some rudimentary signal-quality monitoring was done by such transmitters that basically looked at analogue parameters.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] 3R Transponders were fully digital and normally able to view SONET/SDH section layer overhead bytes such as A1 and A2 to determine signal quality health.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] transponders, which will normally mean the transponder is able to perform 3R regeneration on OC-3/12/48 signals, and possibly gigabit Ethernet, and reporting on signal health by monitoring SONET/SDH section layer overhead bytes.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Many transponders will be able to perform full multi-rate 3R in both directions.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] transponders, which will perform Section layer overhead monitoring to all rates up to and including OC-192.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] (from multiplexed transponder) has different names depending on vendor.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] It essentially performs some relatively simple time-division multiplexing of lower-rate signals into a higher-rate carrier within the system (a common example is the ability to accept 4 OC-48s and then output a single OC-192 in the 1,550 nm band).
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] For DWDM the range between C21-C60 is the most common range, for Mux/Demux in 8, 16, 40 or 96 sizes.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] As mentioned above, intermediate optical amplification sites in DWDM systems may allow for the dropping and adding of certain wavelength channels.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In most systems deployed as of August 2006 this is done infrequently, because adding or dropping wavelengths requires manually inserting or replacing wavelength-selective cards.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is costly, and in some systems requires that all active traffic be removed from the DWDM system because inserting or removing the wavelength-specific cards interrupts the multi-wavelength optical signal.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] With a ROADM, network operators can remotely reconfigure the multiplexer by sending soft commands.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The architecture of the ROADM is such that dropping or adding wavelengths does not interrupt the *pass-through* channels.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Numerous technological approaches are utilized for various commercial ROADMs, the tradeoff being between cost, optical power, and flexibility.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] When the network topology is a mesh, where nodes are interconnected by fibers to form an arbitrary graph, an additional fiber interconnection device is needed to route the signals from an input port to the desired output port.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] These devices are called optical crossconnectors (OXCs).
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Various categories of OXCs include electronic ("opaque"), optical ("transparent"), and wavelength-selective devices.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Cisco's Enhanced WDM system is a network architecture that combines two different types of multiplexing technologies to transmit data over optical fibers.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] EWDM combines 1 Gbit/s Coarse Wave Division Multiplexing (CWDM) connections using SFPs and GBICs with 10 Gbit/s Dense Wave Division Multiplexing (DWDM) connections using XENPAK, X2 or XFP DWDM modules.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The Enhanced WDM system can use either passive or boosted DWDM connections to allow a longer range for the connection.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In addition to this, C form-factor pluggable modules deliver 100 Gbit/s Ethernet suitable for high-speed Internet backbone connections.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Shortwave WDM uses vertical-cavity surface-emitting laser (VCSEL) transceivers with four wavelengths in the 846 to 953 nm range over a single OM5 fiber, or two-fiber connectivity for OM3/OM4 fiber.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] ) communication, two wavelengths will be required if on the same fiber; if separate fibers are used in a so-called fiber pair, then the same wavelength is normally used and it is not WDM.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] As a result, at each end both a transmitter and a receiver will be required.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] A combination of a transmitter and a receiver is called a transceiver; it converts an electrical signal to and from an optical signal.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM transceivers made for single-strand operation require the opposing transmitters to use different wavelengths.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM transceivers additionally require an optical splitter/combiner to couple the transmitter and receiver paths onto the one fiber strand.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In practice, the signal inputs and outputs will not be electrical but optical instead (typically at 1550 nm).
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This means that in effect wavelength converters are needed instead, which is exactly what a transponder is.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] A transponder can be made up of two transceivers placed after each other: the first transceiver converting the 1550 nm optical signal to/from an electrical signal, and the second transceiver converting the electrical signal to/from an optical signal at the required wavelength.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Transponders that don't use an intermediate electrical signal (all-optical transponders) are in development.
[src:optical-networking/wavelength-division-multiplexing] See also transponders (optical communications) for different functional views on the meaning of optical transponders.
